STATE OF MICHIGAN
IN THE CIRCUIT COURT FOR THE COUNTY OF MUSKEGON
FAMILY DIVISION


ANDREW J. PIGORS,
     Plaintiff/Father,
                                                    Case No. 2024-001507-DC
v.                                                  Hon. Jenny L. McNeill

EMILY A. WATSON,
     Defendant/Mother.
_______________________________________/


[PROPOSED] ORDER MODIFYING CUSTODY

     At a session of said Court held at the Muskegon County Courthouse, Muskegon, Michigan, on _____________, 2026.

PRESENT: Honorable Jenny L. McNeill, Circuit Court Judge

     On _____________, 2026, this matter came before the Court on Plaintiff/Father Andrew J. Pigors' Motion to Modify Custody. After reviewing the Motion, Brief in Support, Affidavit, and supporting evidence, [and after hearing testimony and arguments of counsel / the Court being fully advised in the premises], the Court makes the following findings and enters the following order:

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

I. FINDINGS OF FACT

PROCEDURAL HISTORY

     1. On July 17, 2024, this Court entered an Order Regarding Custody and Parenting Time, establishing joint legal custody to both parents, primary physical custody to Defendant/Mother, and parenting time to Plaintiff/Father of 79 overnights per year.

     2. Prior to the July 17, 2024 order, the parties maintained an informal shared parenting arrangement with Father exercising approximately 182.5 overnights per year (50% parenting time).

     3. Plaintiff filed the instant Motion to Modify Custody on February 11, 2026, seeking joint physical custody with equal parenting time or, alternatively, designation as primary physical custodian.

ESTABLISHED CUSTODIAL ENVIRONMENT

     4. The Court finds that an established custodial environment exists with both parents. The child naturally looks to both Father and Mother for guidance, discipline, the necessities of life, and parental comfort. MCL 722.27(1)(c); Foskett v Foskett, 247 Mich App 1 (2001).

     [ALTERNATIVE FINDING: The Court finds that an established custodial environment exists with Mother only.]

PROPER CAUSE

     5. The Court finds by clear and convincing evidence that proper cause exists to modify custody, based on the following grounds:

     a. SYSTEMATIC VIOLATION OF PARENTING TIME: Mother has deprived Father of 329+ days of parenting time since March 2024, including:
          • March 28 - May 5, 2024: 39 days (unilateral withholding)
          • October 20 - November 15, 2024: 26 days (withholding)
          • Various dates: 72 days (schedule violations)
          • August 8, 2025 - Present: 192+ days (ex parte suspension)

     b. FALSE ALLEGATIONS: Mother has made systematic false allegations against Father, including poisoning, assault, suicidality, mental instability, threat, and danger. All allegations have been disproven by medical records, police investigations, and professional evaluation.

     c. PARENTAL ALIENATION: The HealthWest evaluation documents Mother's pattern of gatekeeping, interference, and parental alienation designed to eliminate Father from the child's life.

     d. FRAUDULENT PPO: Mother obtained a Personal Protection Order (Case No. 2023-5907-PP) based on demonstrably false allegations, which has been used to interfere with Father's parenting time.

     e. MATERIAL CHANGES: Since the July 17, 2024 order, the HealthWest evaluation has been completed, Mother's false allegations have been disproven, Mother's pattern of gatekeeping has been professionally documented, and the parent-child relationship has been severely damaged by prolonged deprivation.

     6. These grounds constitute proper cause under MCL 722.27(1)(c) and Shade v Wright, 291 Mich App 17 (2010), as they have a significant effect on the child's life and require reevaluation of custody.

CHANGE OF CIRCUMSTANCES

     7. The Court further finds by clear and convincing evidence that a change of circumstances exists warranting modification, based on:

     a. COMPLETE ELIMINATION OF PARENT-CHILD RELATIONSHIP: Father has been deprived of all contact with the child for 192+ consecutive days (August 8, 2025 - present), representing a complete elimination of the father-child relationship that existed at the time of the July 17, 2024 order.

     b. PROFESSIONAL DOCUMENTATION: The HealthWest evaluation, completed after the July 17, 2024 order, provides professional documentation of Mother's alienation and gatekeeping behaviors and confirms Father's fitness.

     c. ESCALATING FALSE ALLEGATIONS: Mother's false allegations have escalated in frequency and severity since the July 17, 2024 order, with repeated ex parte motions claiming emergencies that do not exist.

     d. DEMONSTRATED UNWILLINGNESS: Mother has demonstrated absolute unwillingness to facilitate the child's relationship with Father, in violation of MCL 722.27a and MCL 722.23(j).

     8. These circumstances have changed since the July 17, 2024 order and have a significant effect on the child requiring reevaluation of custody. Shade v Wright, 291 Mich App 17 (2010).

BEST INTERESTS ANALYSIS (MCL 722.23)

     9. The Court has evaluated the twelve statutory best interest factors under MCL 722.23 and makes the following findings:

     (a) Love, Affection, and Emotional Ties: FAVORS FATHER OR EQUAL. Both parents love the child. Father has maintained a strong emotional bond since birth, exercising approximately 50% parenting time for five years. Mother's systematic deprivation of 329+ days has damaged but not destroyed the father-child bond. The child needs both parents' love and affection.

     (b) Capacity to Provide Love, Affection, and Guidance: FAVORS FATHER. Father has demonstrated appropriate capacity to provide love, affection, and guidance, as confirmed by the HealthWest evaluation. Mother's capacity is compromised by her pattern of false allegations, willingness to use the child as a weapon in litigation, documented alienation behaviors, and prioritization of her conflict with Father over the child's needs.

     (c) Capacity to Provide Material Needs: EQUAL. Both parties have demonstrated capacity to provide food, clothing, medical care, and material needs. Both maintain appropriate housing and stable employment.

     (d) Stable Environment and Continuity: FAVORS MOTHER (OR EQUAL WITH MODIFICATION). Mother has provided the primary residence since July 17, 2024. However, prior to that date, the child maintained stability in both homes under the 50/50 arrangement. The current "stability" has been achieved through unlawful deprivation. True stability includes stability of relationship with both parents. Restoration of meaningful parenting time with Father will restore relational stability.

     (e) Permanence as Family Unit: EQUAL. Both parties can provide permanence as a family unit. Both maintain stable homes and employment.

     (f) Moral Fitness: STRONGLY FAVORS FATHER. Father has no criminal record, no history of dishonesty, and has complied with all court orders. All allegations against him have been disproven. The HealthWest evaluation found no concerns. In contrast, Mother has: (1) systematically made false allegations to law enforcement and courts; (2) obtained a fraudulent PPO through misrepresentation; (3) violated court-ordered parenting time for 329+ days; (4) engaged in documented parental alienation; (5) abused ex parte procedures through false emergency claims; (6) violated MCL 722.27a; and (7) demonstrated a pattern of dishonesty spanning two years. This factor strongly favors Father.

     (g) Mental and Physical Health: STRONGLY FAVORS FATHER. The HealthWest evaluation found Father to have no mental health issues, instability, or safety concerns. All allegations of suicidality and mental instability have been conclusively disproven by medical records and police investigations. This Court's July 17, 2024 order awarding equal legal custody implicitly found Father mentally fit. Mother has no documented mental health concerns, but her pattern of false allegations and alienation behaviors raise questions about judgment and emotional regulation. This factor strongly favors Father.

     (h) Home, School, and Community Record: EQUAL. The child is five years old and of preschool age. Both parties maintain appropriate homes and community connections. Father has been actively involved in the child's developmental activities when permitted parenting time.

     (i) Reasonable Preference of Child: NOT APPLICABLE. The child is five years old and not of sufficient age to express a meaningful custody preference. To the extent the child has expressed any reluctance toward Father, such reluctance is the direct result of Mother's alienation tactics and 329+ days of deprivation, not a "reasonable preference."

     (j) Willingness to Facilitate Relationship: EXTREMELY STRONGLY FAVORS FATHER. This is the most critical factor. Father has: (1) consistently sought to maintain relationship with child; (2) complied with all court orders; (3) never interfered with Mother's parenting time; (4) never made false allegations against Mother; (5) never sought to eliminate Mother from child's life; (6) completed HealthWest evaluation; and (7) demonstrated willingness to co-parent. In contrast, Mother has: (1) deprived Father of 329+ days of parenting time; (2) made systematic false allegations designed to eliminate Father; (3) obtained fraudulent PPO to interfere with parenting time; (4) abused ex parte emergency procedures; (5) engaged in documented parental alienation; and (6) violated MCL 722.27a presumption. Mother has not merely failed to facilitate—she has actively and systematically worked to destroy the father-child relationship through false allegations and abuse of legal process. This factor extremely strongly favors Father. Foskett v Foskett, 247 Mich App 1 (2001); Simons v Gisvold, 236 Mich App 163 (1999).

     (k) Domestic Violence: FAVORS FATHER. There has been no domestic violence. All of Mother's allegations of threat, assault, and danger have been conclusively disproven by police investigations, medical records, the HealthWest evaluation, and this Court's own order awarding equal legal custody. The fraudulent PPO was obtained through misrepresentation, not legitimate domestic violence. False allegations of domestic violence constitute abuse of legal process and abuse of the child's need for both parents. This factor favors Father.

     (l) Any Other Relevant Factor: FAVORS FATHER. Additional relevant factors include: (1) Professional recommendation from HealthWest to restore and expand Father's parenting time; (2) Mother's 329+ days of parenting time violations constitute contempt of court; (3) Mother's false allegations and fraudulent PPO constitute fraud on the court under MCR 2.612; (4) MCL 722.27a establishes statutory presumption that parenting time is in child's best interests (no clear and convincing evidence of endangerment exists); (5) Child's developmental needs require both parents—father involvement is critical for healthy development; (6) Harm from continued deprivation increases each day.

     10. SUMMARY OF BEST INTERESTS: Applying the twelve statutory factors, the Court finds:
          • Factor (a): Favors Father or Equal
          • Factor (b): Favors Father
          • Factor (c): Equal
          • Factor (d): Favors Mother (or Equal with modification)
          • Factor (e): Equal
          • Factor (f): Strongly Favors Father
          • Factor (g): Strongly Favors Father
          • Factor (h): Equal
          • Factor (i): Not Applicable
          • Factor (j): Extremely Strongly Favors Father
          • Factor (k): Favors Father
          • Factor (l): Favors Father

     11. BEST INTERESTS CONCLUSION: Nine (9) of twelve (12) factors favor Father, one (1) favors Mother, and two (2) are equal. The most critical factor—willingness to facilitate the relationship (factor j)—overwhelmingly favors Father. The overwhelming weight of the statutory best interest factors supports modification of custody.

LEGAL CONCLUSIONS

     12. The Court concludes that proper cause and change of circumstances have been established by clear and convincing evidence. MCL 722.27(1)(c); Vodvarka v Grasmeyer, 259 Mich App 499 (2003).

     13. The Court concludes that modification of custody to establish joint physical custody with equal parenting time is in the child's best interests [by clear and convincing evidence / by a preponderance of the evidence]. MCL 722.27(1)(c).

     14. The Court concludes that Mother has violated MCL 722.27a's statutory presumption favoring parenting time. No clear and convincing evidence exists that Father's parenting time would endanger the child. All allegations have been disproven.

     15. The Court concludes that 329+ days of wrongful deprivation of parenting time warrants remedial action, including makeup parenting time and modification of custody.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

II. ORDER

     IT IS HEREBY ORDERED:

A. CUSTODY MODIFICATION GRANTED

     1. Plaintiff/Father's Motion to Modify Custody is GRANTED.

B. LEGAL CUSTODY

     2. Legal custody: The parties shall continue to share joint legal custody, with equal rights and responsibilities for major decisions regarding the child's health, education, and welfare. Neither party may make major decisions without consulting and attempting to reach agreement with the other party.

C. PHYSICAL CUSTODY

     3. Physical custody: The parties shall share joint physical custody, with each party exercising equal parenting time (182.5 overnights per year each, or as close to equal as practical given the calendar).

     [ALTERNATIVE: Physical custody: Plaintiff/Father is designated the primary physical custodian. Defendant/Mother shall exercise parenting time as set forth in the Parenting Time Schedule below.]

D. PARENTING TIME SCHEDULE (EQUAL TIME - OPTION 1: WEEK ON/WEEK OFF)

     4. Regular parenting time schedule:

     Week 1: Father has parenting time from Monday 9:00 AM through Monday 9:00 AM (7 days)
     Week 2: Mother has parenting time from Monday 9:00 AM through Monday 9:00 AM (7 days)

     The schedule alternates weekly throughout the year.

     This schedule provides each parent with 26 weeks per year (182 overnights for Father, 183 overnights for Mother in non-leap years).

[ALTERNATIVE SCHEDULE OPTION 2: 2-2-3 SCHEDULE]

     4. Regular parenting time schedule (2-2-3 rotating):

     Week A:
          Monday-Tuesday: Father (2 days)
          Wednesday-Thursday: Mother (2 days)
          Friday-Saturday-Sunday: Father (3 days)

     Week B:
          Monday-Tuesday: Mother (2 days)
          Wednesday-Thursday: Father (2 days)
          Friday-Saturday-Sunday: Mother (3 days)

     Exchanges occur at 6:00 PM on scheduled transition days.

     This schedule provides each parent with 182.5 overnights per year.

[ALTERNATIVE SCHEDULE OPTION 3: 2-2-5-5 SCHEDULE]

     4. Regular parenting time schedule (2-2-5-5 rotating):

     Week A:
          Monday-Tuesday: Father (2 days)
          Wednesday-Thursday: Mother (2 days)
          Friday-Saturday-Sunday-Monday-Tuesday: Father (5 days)

     Week B:
          Wednesday-Thursday: Father (2 days)
          Friday-Saturday-Sunday-Monday-Tuesday: Mother (5 days)

     Exchanges occur at 6:00 PM on scheduled transition days.

     This schedule provides each parent with 182.5 overnights per year.

E. HOLIDAY AND VACATION SCHEDULE

     5. The regular parenting time schedule shall be modified for holidays and school vacations as follows:

     a. ALTERNATING HOLIDAYS (ODD YEARS WITH FATHER, EVEN YEARS WITH MOTHER):
          • New Year's Day (December 31 6:00 PM through January 1 6:00 PM)
          • Easter (Saturday 6:00 PM through Monday 6:00 PM)
          • Memorial Day (Saturday 6:00 PM through Monday 6:00 PM)
          • July 4th (July 3 6:00 PM through July 5 6:00 PM)
          • Labor Day (Saturday 6:00 PM through Monday 6:00 PM)
          • Thanksgiving (Wednesday 6:00 PM through Sunday 6:00 PM)

     b. ALTERNATING HOLIDAYS (EVEN YEARS WITH FATHER, ODD YEARS WITH MOTHER):
          • Spring Break (First day of spring break 6:00 PM through last day 6:00 PM)
          • Halloween (October 31, 4:00 PM through 8:00 PM)
          • Christmas (December 24 6:00 PM through December 26 6:00 PM)

     c. BIRTHDAY: The child shall spend his birthday with Father on odd years and with Mother on even years (birthday date 4:00 PM through next day 8:00 AM). Birthday celebration shall not replace regular parenting time.

     d. FATHER'S DAY: The child shall spend Father's Day weekend (Saturday 9:00 AM through Sunday 6:00 PM) with Father each year, regardless of the regular schedule.

     e. MOTHER'S DAY: The child shall spend Mother's Day weekend (Saturday 9:00 AM through Sunday 6:00 PM) with Mother each year, regardless of the regular schedule.

     f. SUMMER VACATION: Each parent shall be entitled to two (2) weeks of uninterrupted summer parenting time (to be selected by May 1 each year, with Father selecting first in odd years and Mother selecting first in even years). Summer vacation weeks shall not conflict with the other parent's selected weeks. Notice of selected weeks shall be provided to the other parent by May 15 each year.

F. EXCHANGES

     6. Exchanges shall occur at [location to be specified] or such other location as the parties may agree.

     7. The party beginning parenting time shall be responsible for picking up the child. The party ending parenting time shall have the child ready for pickup at the scheduled time.

     8. Each party shall ensure that the child is clean, fed, rested, and has weather-appropriate clothing and any necessary medications or special items for the exchange.

     9. Both parties shall conduct themselves appropriately during exchanges. There shall be no arguing, confrontation, or negative comments about the other party in the child's presence.

G. COMMUNICATION

     10. Communication regarding the child: The parties shall communicate regarding the child's welfare, health, education, and schedule via [text message / email / co-parenting app] or telephone. Communication shall be respectful, businesslike, and focused on the child's needs.

     11. Communication with child: Each party shall facilitate reasonable telephone and video communication between the child and the other parent during parenting time. The child shall have the right to speak with the other parent by telephone or video call once per day at a reasonable time (not to exceed 15 minutes per call). Neither party shall monitor or interfere with such calls.

H. MAKEUP PARENTING TIME

     12. Father is awarded 329 days of makeup parenting time to compensate for wrongful deprivation from March 2024 through February 2026.

     13. This makeup time shall be scheduled at Father's discretion over the next 18 months (through August 11, 2027), in blocks of no less than three (3) consecutive days each.

     14. Father shall provide Mother with at least 14 days' written notice of each block of makeup time.

     15. Makeup time shall be in addition to regular parenting time and shall not reduce Mother's regular parenting time except as necessary to accommodate the makeup blocks.

     16. Mother shall fully cooperate with scheduling and exercise of makeup parenting time and shall not interfere in any way.

I. FACILITATION OF RELATIONSHIP

     17. Both parties are ORDERED to comply with MCL 722.27a and to facilitate and encourage a close and continuing relationship between the child and the other parent.

     18. Neither party shall make negative comments about the other party to the child or in the child's presence.

     19. Neither party shall interrogate the child about the other parent's activities, household, or relationships.

     20. Neither party shall interfere with the other party's parenting time or communication with the child.

     21. Mother is specifically ORDERED to cease all gatekeeping, alienation, and interference behaviors as documented in the HealthWest evaluation.

J. COMPLIANCE WITH ORDERS

     22. Both parties shall strictly comply with this Order and with all provisions of MCL 722.27a.

     23. Willful violation of this Order may result in contempt proceedings, modification of custody, attorney fees, and other sanctions.

K. EX PARTE ORDERS VACATED

     24. All prior ex parte orders suspending Father's parenting time are hereby VACATED, specifically including the orders dated August 8, 2025, September 4, 2025, October 29, 2025, November 26, 2025, and December 17, 2025.

     25. Father's parenting time is immediately restored pursuant to the schedule set forth in this Order.

L. PERSONAL PROTECTION ORDER

     26. The Court makes no findings in this order regarding the Personal Protection Order in Case No. 2023-5907-PP, which remains a separate proceeding. [However, the Court notes that the evidence in this case strongly suggests that the PPO was obtained through misrepresentation, and Father is encouraged to file appropriate motions in that case.]

M. CHILD SUPPORT

     27. Child support: [The parties shall exchange financial information and calculate child support pursuant to the Michigan Child Support Formula. / Child support shall be recalculated based on the equal parenting time arrangement and submitted to the Court within 30 days. / No child support shall be owed given equal parenting time and substantially equal incomes.]

N. ATTORNEY FEES AND COSTS

     28. Attorney fees and costs: Mother is ORDERED to pay Father's reasonable attorney fees and costs incurred in bringing this Motion, in the amount of $________, based on Mother's bad faith conduct in violating parenting time, making false allegations, and necessitating this Motion. MCR 3.206(C).

     [ALTERNATIVE: Each party shall bear their own attorney fees and costs.]

O. EFFECTIVE DATE

     29. This Order is effective immediately upon entry and supersedes the July 17, 2024 Order Regarding Custody and Parenting Time.

P. RESERVATION OF JURISDICTION

     30. The Court reserves jurisdiction to enforce this Order and to make further orders as necessary to serve the child's best interests.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

IT IS SO ORDERED.


